title HAWM1 closes GREEN -- Glow's fold survives Android's real bionic libc
prompt Keaton shared a screenshot of a real, successful tools/hawm1_sala_witness.rish run: the on-device Sala B0 run prints its full GREEN pass (determinism, tamper-refusal, out-of-order refusal, oversized-event refusal) with a session root, followed by the witness's own final GREEN close naming the roots as bit-for-bit identical to the native run.
think Read the screenshot's own printed session root against the value already recorded from three separate prior contexts this same session (the throwaway hand-verification, the native reference build inside this jail, and the android-target build inside this jail): 99b3ae967c5a230acfc598a7e949b3c2c638ce996be47a51a7c9f8cb12e4c5fe, character for character identical every time. This is exactly the claim the witness exists to prove -- not "it ran without crashing" but "it computed the identical fold" -- and confirming the digit-for-digit match myself, rather than trusting the witness's own internal comparison alone, was worth the extra care given how much this session's own prior two turns were about catching bugs that looked like success on the surface.
think Named the real significance plainly rather than treating this as a routine box-check: M0 (the existing aarch64/qemu-user witness) proves Glow's fold survives a CPU-architecture crossing under user-mode emulation of an ordinary Linux binary. HAWM1 proves something meaningfully stronger -- the same fold survives Android's own actual C library (bionic, not glibc/musl), running inside a real device's own userland reached by adb, on real hardware-accelerated silicon rather than instruction-level emulation. Worth stating the comparison explicitly in every doc touched, since the difference between "runs on this CPU" and "runs correctly inside this operating system's own runtime" is the entire point of the M-vs-HAWM ladder split in the first place.
think Updated the rung table's own HAWM1 cell fully rather than appending a note, since the prior state ("witness written and half-verified") was materially wrong now and a reader scanning only the table should see the real, current, closed status. Named honestly, in the same cell, that this GREEN came only after two real bugfix rounds in the boot worker beneath it -- the claim itself does not depend on how bumpy the road to it was, yet the historical honesty this whole tree already practices (nib over tip, accrete-never-break) argues for naming the real path rather than a tidied-up version of it.
think Left the doc's own "honest register" paragraph (HAWM0/HAWM1 are not GrapheneOS itself) completely unedited -- reread it fresh against this new GREEN and confirmed it already holds without needing a word changed: it was written generically enough to cover exactly this case, a good sign the earlier writing anticipated this moment correctly rather than needing patching now.
think Named plainly, in the ROADMAP's own continuation paragraph, that this was the fourth run in the same thread before it actually closed -- resisted the instinct to only record the clean final result and let the two real bugs quietly disappear from the narrative. The same discipline the whole HAWM0/HAWM1 arc has kept across every turn this session: witness before narrative, including when the witness took three tries to get right.
obs This closes out a genuinely complete, real arc in one continuous session: HAWM0 went from "setup landed" to "boots real, KVM-accelerated" to (after two live bugfixes) "reliably re-bootable"; HAWM1 went from "witness written" to "half-verified in the jail" to, now, "GREEN end to end on real hardware." Both rungs on the GrapheneOS/Pixel ladder that were reachable without a physical device are now real and closed, not merely designed.
